1 Sec. 21. 25 MRSA §2926, as amended by PL 2023, c. 186, §2, is further amended
2 to read:
3 §2926. Emergency Services Communication Bureau
4 1. Bureau established. The Emergency Services Communication Bureau is
5 established within the Public Utilities Commission to implement and manage E-9-1-1
6 9-1-1, including the deployment of E-9-1-1 9-1-1 service using emerging communications
7 technologies, including, but not limited to, Internet protocol enabled services, that are
8 capable of connecting users to public safety answering points.
9 1-A. Quality assurance. The bureau shall develop and implement a quality assurance
10 program to audit and monitor compliance with emergency dispatching standards, practices
11 and procedures of public safety answering points.
12 2. System design. In consultation with the E-9-1-1 9-1-1 Council, established in Title
13 5, section 12004-I, subsection 74-A, the bureau shall develop all necessary system
14 elements, standards and cost estimates necessary to provide for the installation and
15 operation of a statewide E-9-1-1 9-1-1 system, including, but not limited to, the following:
16 A. Development of network design specifications;
17 B. Development of minimum public safety answering point requirements including
18 24-hour operation; emergency backup power; secured communication areas; separate
19 administrative phone lines for nonemergency calls; call recording and playback
20 equipment; TDD equipment, as defined in Title 35‑A, section 8702, subsection 6;
21 maximum call handling times; and minimum mandatory staff training requirements for
22 9-1-1 call answering and dispatching;
23 C. After consultation with the affected public and private safety agency officials,
24 identification of appropriate public safety answering point sites based on consideration
25 of the existing dispatching capabilities of public and private safety agencies, the
26 expressed preferences of municipalities throughout the State and overall system cost;
27 D. Identification of appropriate technology for system networks, public safety
28 answering point equipment and data base database requirements;
29 E. Procedures for developing and maintaining address and routing data bases database;
30 F. Procedures for cooperation and coordination with telephone utilities and
31 municipalities for implementation and maintenance;
32 G. Standards and procedures to establish the confidentiality and prevent the
33 dissemination of reports and records handled by public safety answering points and of
34 the bureau;
35 H. Estimates of the cost of establishing an operational E-9-1-1 9-1-1 system;
36 I. Procedures for collecting and administering the necessary funds for E-9-1-1 9-1-1;
37 and
38 J. Standards and procedures for developing and maintaining the system databases and
39 for ensuring the confidentiality of those databases pursuant to section 2929.
40 2-A. Goal. To the extent possible, the bureau shall establish a total of between 16 and
41 24 public safety answering points. The bureau shall seek to coordinate any reduction in
42 the number of public safety answering points to achieve this goal with any contractual
Page 5 - 132LR0556(01)

413 obligations it may have or may enter into that are or could be affected by that reduction.
424 Prior to implementing a reduction in the number of public safety answering points, the
435 bureau shall make a finding regarding the need for the reduction based on an evaluation of
446 the costs and benefits of the reduction, taking into account impacts on ratepayers, each of
457 the affected municipalities municipality, plantation, county or unorganized territory and
468 the State.
7 2-B. Exceptions. Notwithstanding subsection 2‑A, the bureau may authorize the
8 establishment of a public safety answering point on a determination that a public safety
9 answering point is necessary to ensure public safety and access to E-9-1-1 9-1-1 services.
10 3. Rulemaking. The bureau Public Utilities Commission shall adopt by rule its the
11 bureau's standards, specifications and procedures developed under subsection 2,
12 paragraphs A to F after consultation with the E-9-1-1 9-1-1 Council and following at least
13 3 public hearings geographically dispersed throughout the State.
14 4. Technical assistance. The bureau may provide support for the development of
15 street address information sufficient to support E-9-1-1 9-1-1 services. The bureau shall
16 provide technical assistance to any municipality in the development of street address
17 information at the request of the interested municipality, plantation, county or unorganized
18 territory.
19 5. Call answering coverage. The bureau is not required to provide call answering
20 coverage in counties or municipalities that choose not to participate in the E-9-1-1 system.
21 6. System databases. The system databases, wherever located or stored, are the
22 property of the bureau and their confidentiality is governed by section 2929.
23 Sec. 22. 25 MRSA §2927, as amended by PL 2023, c. 609, §4, is repealed.
24 Sec. 23. 25 MRSA §2927-A is enacted to read:
25 §2927-A. 9-1-1 funding
26 1. Funding. The activities authorized under this chapter are funded through:
27 A. The statewide 9-1-1 surcharge under subsection 2 levied on:
28 (1) Each residential and business telephone exchange line, including private
29 branch exchange lines and Centrex lines;
30 (2) Semipublic coin and public access lines;
31 (3) Customers of interconnected voice over Internet protocol service; and
32 (4) Customers of cellular or wireless telecommunications service that is not a
33 prepaid wireless telecommunications service. A surcharge may not be levied under
34 this subparagraph with respect to customers of cellular or wireless
35 telecommunications service that is supported by federal universal service support
36 funds pursuant to 47 Code of Federal Regulations, Part 54; and
37 B. The statewide prepaid wireless telecommunications service 9-1-1 surcharge under
38 subsection 3 levied on prepaid wireless telecommunications service customers. A
39 surcharge may not be levied under this paragraph with respect to prepaid wireless
40 telecommunications service supported by federal universal service support funds
41 pursuant to 47 Code of Federal Regulations, Part 54, except that a surcharge may be
Page 6 - 132LR0556(01)

412 levied under this paragraph on transactions in which the customer directly purchases
423 optional services that are not supported by federal universal service support funds.
3 2. Statewide 9-1-1 surcharge. The statewide 9-1-1 surcharge is governed by this
4 subsection.
5 A. The Public Utilities Commission shall establish the statewide 9-1-1 surcharge,
6 except that the statewide 9-1-1 surcharge may not exceed 35¢ per month per line or
7 number. The commission shall establish the statewide 9-1-1 surcharge by rule or
8 through other commission proceedings. The statewide 9-1-1 surcharge may not be
9 imposed on more than 25 lines or numbers per customer billing account.
10 B. The statewide 9-1-1 surcharge must be collected from the customer according to
11 subsection 1, paragraph A on a monthly basis by each local exchange telephone utility,
12 cellular or wireless telecommunications service provider and interconnected voice over
13 Internet protocol service provider and be shown separately as a statewide 9-1-1
14 surcharge on the customer's bill.
15 C. The place of residence of cellular or wireless telecommunications service customers
16 who are not prepaid wireless telecommunications service customers must be
17 determined according to the sourcing rules for mobile telecommunications services as
18 set forth in Title 36, section 2556.
19 3. Statewide prepaid wireless telecommunications service 9-1-1 surcharge. The
20 statewide prepaid wireless telecommunications service 9-1-1 surcharge, referred to in this
21 subsection as "the prepaid wireless 9-1-1 surcharge," is governed by this subsection.
22 The Public Utilities Commission shall establish the prepaid wireless 9-1-1 surcharge,
23 except that the prepaid wireless 9-1-1 surcharge may not exceed 35¢ per retail transaction.
24 The commission shall establish the prepaid wireless 9-1-1 surcharge by rule or through
25 other commission proceedings.
26 4. 9-1-1 funding obligation; limitation. The statewide 9-1-1 surcharge imposed by
27 subsection 2 and the prepaid wireless 9-1-1 surcharge imposed by subsection 3 are the only
28 9-1-1 funding obligations imposed with respect to telecommunications service in this State,
29 and another tax, fee, surcharge or other charge may not be imposed by this State, a political
30 subdivision of this State or an intergovernmental agency for funding 9-1-1 purposes on any
31 telecommunications service with respect to the sale, purchase, use or provision of that
32 telecommunications service.
33 5. Surcharge remittance. Each local exchange telephone utility, cellular or wireless
34 telecommunications service provider and interconnected voice over Internet protocol
35 service provider shall remit the statewide 9-1-1 surcharge revenues collected from
36 customers pursuant to subsection 1 on a monthly basis and within one month of the month
37 collected, except that a utility or provider whose average monthly surcharge remittance
38 payment for the prior calendar year is less than $5,000 shall remit the 9-1-1 surcharge
39 revenues on a quarterly basis, to the Treasurer of State for deposit in a separate account
40 known as and referred to in this section as "the 9-1-1 fund." Each telephone utility or
41 service provider required to remit statewide 9-1-1 surcharge revenues shall provide, on a
42 form approved by the bureau, supporting data, including, but not limited to, the following:
43 A. The calculation used to arrive at the surcharge remittance amount;
44 B. The calculation used to arrive at the uncollectible amount of surcharge;
Page 7 - 132LR0556(01)

1 C. The total surcharge;
2 D. The month and year or the quarter and year for which a surcharge is remitted;
3 E. The legal name and telephone number of the telephone utility or service provider
4 and, if applicable, the parent company name, address and telephone number; and
5 F. The name and telephone number of the person who prepared the form.
6 Prepaid wireless 9-1-1 surcharges collected by sellers must be remitted to the State Tax
7 Assessor in accordance with Title 35‑A, section 7104‑C.
8 6. Expenditure of funds. All costs incurred by the bureau under this subsection must
9 be paid from the 9-1-1 fund.
10 A. The bureau may use the revenues in the 9-1-1 fund to:
11 (1) Fund staff;
12 (2) Defray the costs associated with the implementation, operation and
13 management of 9-1-1, including the deployment of 9-1-1 service using emerging
14 communications technologies, including, but not limited to, Internet protocol
15 enabled services, that are capable of connecting users to public safety answering
16 points; and
17 (3) Defray the costs, including necessary staffing costs, of the Emergency Medical
18 Services' Board in implementing the requirements of Title 32, section 85‑A
19 through the transfer of funds to the Other Special Revenue Funds, Emergency
20 Medical Services account within the Department of Public Safety.
21 B. The bureau shall use the revenues in the 9-1-1 fund to:
22 (1) Provide free training courses for emergency medical dispatchers, as defined in
23 Title 32, section 85‑A, subsection 1, paragraph D, to assist public safety answering
24 points in meeting the requirements of Title 32, section 85‑A;
25 (2) Provide each public safety answering point a sufficient number of approved
26 Emergency Medical Dispatch Priority Reference System documents in printed or
27 electronic format, as determined by the bureau pursuant to Title 32, section 85‑A;
28 (3) Provide public safety answering points dispatcher training consistent with the
29 protocols, necessary software and printed support materials to assist public safety
30 answering points in the adoption and implementation of standardized dispatch
31 protocols for answering fire 9-1-1 calls;
32 (4) Provide quality assurance training and software to assist public safety
33 answering points in ensuring compliance with the standardized dispatch protocols
34 for answering fire 9-1-1 calls;
35 (5) Provide, subject to available funds not to exceed $1,000,000 per biennium,
36 grants for nonrecurring costs to:
37 (a) Dispatch centers associated with the consolidation of the dispatch centers
38 into public safety answering points;
39 (b) Consolidate 2 or more public safety answering points and dispatch centers
40 into a new regional public safety answering point and dispatch center; or
Page 8 - 132LR0556(01)

1 (c) Transfer a public safety answering point and all of its dispatch services to
2 another existing public safety answering point; and
3 (6) Contract with one or more 3rd‑party vendors to provide quality assurance
4 review in accordance with rules adopted pursuant to subsection 11 and Title 32,
5 section 85‑A, subsection 2 related to the provision of emergency medical dispatch
6 services and answering fire 9-1-1 calls by public safety answering points.
7 7. Unexpended funds; interest. The amount of the 9-1-1 fund not expended by the
8 end of the fiscal year may not lapse but must be carried forward to be expended for the
9 purposes specified in this chapter in succeeding fiscal years. The Treasurer of State shall
10 credit all interest on fund balances to the 9-1-1 fund.
11 8. Legislative annual report. The bureau shall include in the Public Utilities
12 Commission's annual report pursuant to Title 35‑A, section 120, subsection 7 to the joint
13 standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over utilities and energy matters:
14 A. The bureau's planned expenditures for the year and use of funds for the previous
15 year;
16 B. The statewide 9-1-1 surcharge collected under this section;
17 C. The bureau's recommended statewide 9-1-1 surcharge for the coming year;
18 D. The bureau's recommendations for amending existing and enacting new laws to
19 improve the 9-1-1 system; and
20 E. The performance of each of the public safety answering points in the State during
21 the previous calendar year, including the results of the bureau's quality assurance
22 program audits under section 2926, subsection 1‑A and any recommendations of the
23 bureau relating to the emergency dispatching standards, practices and procedures of
24 public safety answering points.
25 9. Committee recommendations; budget. The joint standing committee of the
26 Legislature having jurisdiction over utilities and energy matters shall make
27 recommendations to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction
28 over appropriations and financial affairs regarding all expenditures from the 9-1-1 fund.
29 10. Violations. A telephone utility, a cellular or wireless telecommunications service
30 provider, including a prepaid wireless telephone service provider, or an interconnected
31 voice over Internet protocol service provider subject to this section that intentionally and
32 knowingly fails to remit the statewide 9-1-1 surcharge revenues collected under this section
33 commits a civil violation for which a fine of not more than $500 may be adjudged for each
34 day that payment is not made after the due date.
35 11. Rules. The Public Utilities Commission shall adopt rules necessary to implement
36 the provisions of this section. Rules adopted under this subsection are routine technical
37 rules as defined in Title 5, chapter 375, subchapter 2‑A.
