33 This paragraph is repealed October 1, 2025.
34 SUMMARY
3355 This bill does the following:
36 1. It updates and adds terminology to be consistent with modernized 9-1-1 systems
37 and federal standards;
38 2. It clarifies rule-making authority by designating the Public Utilities Commission as
39 the entity responsible for rulemaking instead of the Emergency Services Communication
40 Bureau within the commission and makes all rulemaking under the emergency services
41 communication laws routine technical;
42 3. It reorganizes the provisions of law related to 9-1-1 funding;
Page 15 - 132LR0556(01)

1 4. It expands the granting authority of the bureau to allow grants, subject to available
2 funds, to be used to consolidate 2 or more public safety answering points and dispatch
3 centers into a new regional public safety answering point and dispatch center or transfer a
4 public safety answering point and all of its dispatch services to another existing public
5 safety answering point. It also changes the allowable funding cap for nonrecurring costs to
6 $1,000,000 per biennium;
7 5. It removes the requirement that the bureau reimburse local exchange carriers and
8 cellular and wireless telecommunications service providers for eligible expenses incurred
9 by the carriers and service providers;
10 6. It removes the requirement regarding the inclusion of 9-1-1 information in telephone
11 directories; and
12 7. It expands the application of provisions related to the information required to be
13 provided to the commission in order to maintain the 9-1-1 database and services and the
14 coordination of 9-1-1 service from local exchange carriers only to originating service
15 providers.
